ional developments, but in their interactions. Drawing on original archival sources, Ali Yaycioglu uncovers the patterns of political action-the making and unmaking of coalitions, forms of building and losing power, and expressions of public opinion. Countering common assumptions, he shows that the Ottoman transformation in the Age of Revolutions was not a linear transition from the old order to the new, from decentralized state to centralized, from Eastern to Western institutions, or from pre-modern to modern. Rather, it was a condensed period of transformation that counted many crossing paths, as well as dead-ends, all of which offered a rich repertoire of governing possibilities to be followed, reinterpreted, or ultimately forgotten.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aPolitical culturezTurkeyxHistoryy18th century. 0aPolitical culturezTurkeyxHistoryy19th century. 0aPolitical participationzTurkeyxHistoryy18th century. 0aPolitical participationzTurkeyxHistoryy19th century. 4a18th century. 4aAge of Revolutions. 4aCommunities. 4aNotables. 4aOttoman Empire. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / Turkey & Ottoman Empire.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311070397940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804798389zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804798389423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804798389.jpg  a978-3-11-070397-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles